  <title translate="true">RIP: Riparian Evapotranspiration Package Pane</title>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">RIP: Riparian Evapotranspiration Package Pane</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">RIP: Riparian Evapotranspiration package</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> pane is on the </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MODFLOW_Features_Tab" styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">MODFLOW Features</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> tab of the </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="Object_Properties_Dialog_Box" styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Object Properties</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> dialog box.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">It is used to define the ground surface elevation and the fractional coverage of each plant group in the cells in the </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="RIP_Riparian_Pkg" styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Riparian Evapotranspiration</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> package of MDOFLOW-OWHM.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">The ground surface elevation within a cell may be varied by defining multiple objects that either intersect or enclose the center of the cell. Each such object can define a different ground surface elevation. However, it is important to note that formulas that are always evaluated at the centers of objects.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">One way to assign the coverages for the plant groups would be to use non-overlapping polygon objects that have both </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="Properties_Tab" anchor="SetValues" styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Set values of enclosed cells</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">, and </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="Properties_Tab" anchor="SetValues" styleclass="Normal" style="font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Set values of intersected cells</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> checked. Each polygon object would define a non-zero coverage for just one plant group. The formula &quot;ObjectIntersectArea / BlockAreaTop&quot;  would return the proper coverage for each cell. If an object would define non-zero coverages for for more than one plant group, the above formula could be multiplied by the fraction of each plant group within the polygon object.</text></para>
  </body>
